Serialising interfaces doesn't work

**Describe the bug**

Hello.
I'm trying to follow the docs at https://github.com/Kotlin/kotlinx.serialization/blob/master/docs/polymorphism.md#serializing-interfaces, but I can't manage to make it work unless I specify the hierarchy by hand.

Error:
```console
kotlinx.serialization.SerializationException: Serializer for subclass 'MarketModelTypologyElement' is not found in the polymorphic scope of 'Element'.
Check if class with serial name 'MarketModelTypologyElement' exists and serializer is registered in a corresponding SerializersModule.
To be registered automatically, class 'MarketModelTypologyElement' has to be '@Serializable', and the base class 'Element' has to be sealed and '@Serializable'.
```

By hand registration which works:
```kotlin
val format = Json {
    serializersModule = SerializersModule {
        polymorphic(Element::class) {
            subclass(MarketModelTypologyElement::class)
        }
    }
    classDiscriminator = "@class"
}
```

**To Reproduce**
```kotlin
interface Element: Writable, Sizeable {
    val id: UByte
    fun getId() = id.toInt()

    override fun write(out: BitOutputStream) = out.writeUByte(id)
}

@Serializable
data class MarketModelTypologyElement(val type: Short, val information: String): Element {
    override val id = ID
    private val informationAscii by lazy { information.toByteArray(CHARSET) }
    @Suppress("MemberVisibilityCanBePrivate") val elementLength get() = (PREFIX_SIZE_BYTES + informationAscii.size).toUShort()
    override val sizeBytes get() = 1u + elementLength

    fun getElementLength() = elementLength.toInt()

    override fun write(out: BitOutputStream) {
        super.write(out)
        out.writeUShort(elementLength)
        out.writeShort(type)
        out.writeBytes(informationAscii)
    }
}
```

The issue occurs, though, only with Elements which are part of ContainerElements (used as `List<ContainerElement> containerElements`):
```kotlin
@Serializable
data class ContainerElement(val elements: List<Element>): Element {
    override val id = ID
    @Suppress("MemberVisibilityCanBePrivate") val elementLength get() = (2u + elements.fastSumOf { it.sizeBytes }).toUShort()
    fun getElementLength() = elementLength.toInt()
    override val sizeBytes get() = 1u + elementLength

    init {
        require(elements.isNotEmpty()) { "A container element must have at least one element" }
    }

    @SafeVarargs
    constructor(vararg element: Element): this(listOf(*element))

    override fun write(out: BitOutputStream) {
        super.write(out)
        out.writeUShort(elementLength)
        elements.fastForEach { it.write(out) }
    }
```

**Expected behavior**

There should be no needed to register all the subtypes of `Element` by hand.


**Environment**
 - Kotlin version: 2.3.20
 - Library version: 1.11.0
 - Kotlin platforms: JVM
 - Gradle version: N/A (Maven 3.9.x)
 - IDE version (if bug is related to the IDE) IntelliJ IDEA 2025.3.4
 - Other relevant context Azul JDK 25

R8 removes the `job` GC-anchor field from `ReadonlySharedFlow`/`ReadonlyStateFlow`

The fix for [#2557](https://github.com/Kotlin/kotlinx.coroutines/issues/2557) ([fbac730](https://github.com/pablobaxter/kotlinx.coroutines/commit/fbac73096a61c8b45c995a2320f139a87e5c9333)) added a `private val job: Job?` field to `ReadonlySharedFlow` and `ReadonlyStateFlow` to prevent the sharing coroutine from being garbage collected. The field is annotated `@Suppress("unused")`, which silences the Kotlin compiler but has no effect on bytecode-level optimizers.

R8's full-mode optimizer removes fields that are written but never read. Since `job` is never read, R8 strips the field and its constructor assignment, making the sharing coroutine eligible for GC again.

**This will affect all Android projects once AGP 9.0 is adopted**, because it [drops support for `proguard-android.txt`](https://android-developers.googleblog.com/2025/11/use-r8-to-shrink-optimize-and-fast.html), which had `-dontoptimize`.

## Reproduction

Tested with:
- kotlinx-coroutines 1.10.2
- R8 8.13.19
- Kotlin 2.3.20
- JDK 17

The reproduction code is adapted from the original issue. A `callbackFlow` with a `WeakReference`-based callback (mimicking Android APIs like `SharedPreferences` or `MediaPlayer`) is shared via `stateIn`. Without the `job` GC anchor, the sharing coroutine is collected and emissions stop.

